I did a whole ton of travel for work between about 2010 and 2014. It's a lonely existence and you can only stand to do so many team/customer dinners.

I kept a soc.txt file, just a list of people who looked interesting in whatever threads I was reading, what cities they lived in, and how to get in touch with them. Once a city showed up on my schedule, I'd send out a few notes, basically, "Hi, we talked a bit in this thread a while back. I've got a work trip to your city coming up, and I'll buy you dinner if you want to come hang out for a couple hours."

Most of the time I'd get at least one or two takers, and usually some recommendations for better local restaurant than what was near the hotel, maybe a show that was in town.

It was fun! I must have met a hundred people that way. Sometimes we'd stay in touch, usually not. Over the years, I did wind up taking a few people back to the room, but that wasn't my goal. Really I just enjoyed the companionship and the chance to meet people I wouldn't ordinarily; I got to hear a lot of stories that were way outside my own life experiences (and a couple that were really sad), and I think that was good for me as a person.

I did meet 2-3 real standout weirdos. One guy painfully bad incel vibes. One girl was a turboNEET and went in super hard on how work was a scam and she didn't feel she should have to do any. She was pretty cute and I would have liked spending more time with her if she had a better personality, but she was so blatantly pushing for me to spend the whole week spending my per diem on her that it was offputting. One guy was just navyseals.txt copypasta personified.

I quit that job for a better one, and even if I miss some of the lifestyle I'm glad I'm not doing it anymore. /Soc/ had pretty well lost the "friendly banter" feel by the end, so I look around and I'm not sure how I'd feel about doing that today.
